site_name: Phases 1-4, Havelock Estate (Affecting Properties In Havelock Road,

protected_spaces_details.description: Provision for children and young people

application_type_full: Outline planning permission: Some matters reserved
description: Outline planning application detailing Access, Layout and Scale (and reserving Landscaping and Appearance for later determination) for the phased demolition of 692 existing residential units, seven commercial units with 490sqm floor space in a A1 (retail) and D1 (non-residential institutions) use classes and other associated structures; the retention of 154 existing residential units and the phased construction of a maximum of 922 new residential units with 3,546 habitable rooms in a mixture of apartment buildings varying between four and eight storeys high and two, three and four storey houses; 840sq.m floor space in commercial use (A1/A3 Use Classes); 280sq.m floorspace in D1 (non-residential institutions) use class; refuse and recycling facilities; bicycle storage facilities; approximately 880 car parking spaces; landscaping including new public open spaces and children's play areas, associated public realm and highways works. This application constitutes a Departure from the Local Plan.
decision_conditions: a) Applications for the approval of Reserved Matters must be made no later than the expiration of ten (10) years beginning with the date of this outline planning permission, and b) The development to which the permission relates must be begun no later than the expiration of two (2) years from the final approval of the Reserved Matters, or in the case of approval on different dates, the final approval of the last such matter to be approved.  Reason: To comply with Section 92 of the Town and Country Planning Act 1990 (as amended). | No part of the development in Phases 2-4, as illustrated on approved Masterplan Phasing drawing PL_Out_007 A shall commence until all of the following reserved matters for that Phase have been approved by the Local Planning Authority:  A) Appearance, and B) Landscaping  The relevant Phase of development shall be carried out in accordance with the approved documents and plans.  Reason: To ensure that the Local Planning Authority may be satisfied with the details of the proposal as provided for in Article 4 and 5 of the Town and Country Planning (Development Management Procedure) Order 2010, as this application is in outline form only. | The development hereby approved shall be carried out in accordance with the following approved plans and documents insofar as they will be amended subject to the approved plans and documents necessary to support the reserved matters application(s) required by the various conditions of this permission:  (390_PL_Out_): 001A, 002 C, 003 A, 004 A, 005 A, 006 A, 007 A, 008 C, 009 A, 010 C, 011 B, 012 C, 013C, 014 B, 015 C, 100 B, 101 A, 102 A, 200 A, 201 A, 250 A, 251 A, 252 A, 253 A, 254 A, 255 A, 256 A; (IA-350-): LMP-P01 A, LGA-P01 A, LGA-P02 A, LGA-P03 A, LGA-P04 A, LS-P02 A, LS-P03 A, TP-P01 A, TP-P02 A, TP-P03 A, TP-P04 A;   Masterplan Design & Access Statement (dated July 2013 and updated by 'Addendum for Planning October 2013', prepared by PTEa and Ireland Albrecht Landscape Architects); Design Code (dated July 2013 and updated by Design Code Addendum, October 2013 Rev A, prepared by PTEa); Planning & Regeneration Statement (Project ref: 21744/A5/Planning Statement Issue 03, dated 02/07/2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore Ltd); Affordable Housing Statement (Ref: 21744/A5, July 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore Ltd); Ecological Scoping Survey (dated December, 2012 and prepared by Furesfen), Habitat and Breeding Bird Survey Report (dated May 2013 and prepared by Furesfen), Bat Survey Report (and addendum including fourth bat survey on 23/07/2013 and prepared by Furesfen); Arboricultural Implications Assessment and Arboricultural Method Statement (Ref: AIA30-4-13, 05/06/2013, prepared by M.Clews on behalf of Arborhelp) and BS5837 Survey & Initial Work Schedule for Trees Surveyed at Havelock Estate (prepared by M. Clews on behalf of Arborhelp) and accompanying drawings 30-4-13-001-A-survey-final, 30-4-13-001-A-survey-b, 30-4-13-001-A-survey-c, 30-4-13-001-A-survey-d, 30-4-13-001-A-survey-e; Health Impact Assessment (Project ref: 21744/A5/VL/HIA, June 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore Ltd); Socio Economics Report (Project ref: 21744/A5, dated July 2013, prepared by Barton Wilmore LLP); Heritage Statement (ref: LH/14931, July 2013, prepared by CgMs Ltd); Wind Environment Assessment (Issue 2, Project ref: 00037231-001, dated 28/06/2013, prepared by ); Air Quality Assessment (Ref: 27760/005 Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP); Noise Assessment (Ref: 27760-006/Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP); Prelimary Contamination Assessment (Ref: DMB/770050b/R1, August 2013, prepared by MLM Consulting Engineers Ltd); Lighting Impact Appraisal Assessment (Ref: 27760/Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP); Sunlight, Daylight and Overshadowing Assessment (ref: 32992/IM/nms, dated 08/07/2013, prepared by Malcolm Hollis LLP); Addendum to Transport Assessment (including vehicle tracking diagrams) (ref: 27760-001 Doc ref: 01, dated 16/10/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates), Transport Technical Note (ref: 27760-001, dated 07/10/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates); Construction Management Plan (no ref & un-dated, prepared by Leadbitter Group); Flood Risk Assessment (Project Ref: 27760/Issue 1, May 2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates); Sustainability Report including updated Appendix 5 (Ref: EST6090 Issue 1, 10/07/2013, prepared by Bespoke Builder Services Ltd), Addednum II Sustainability Report (Ref: EST-6090/add II Issue 1, October 2013, prepared by Bespoke Builder Services Ltd); Statement of Community Involvement (Prepared by Catalyst Housing Ltd); Utilities & Foul Drainage Assessment (Ref: 27760/001 Issue 1, 03/07/2013, prepared by Peter Brett Associates LLP).  Reason: For the avoidance of doubt and in the interests of proper planning. | Each Reserved Matters submission shall include the following information relative to that Phase / reserved matters area:  A) Updated Design and Access Statement and supporting Design Code, which shall provide details of how the design principles and commitments established by the approved Design and Access Statement and Design Code are achieved; B) Floor, elevation and section plans; C) Roofs plans showing the array of photovoltaic panels and biodiversity roofs; D) Details of ground floor level shopfronts (where proposed); E) Details of the internal space standards, unit-size mix, Lifetime Homes and Wheelchair Standards of residential units; F) Updated Energy / Sustainability Assessment Report providing details of the measures to achieve on-site total regulated C02 emissions reduction in accordance with the percentage savings contained under policy 5.2 of the London Plan 2011 (including any subsequent revisions to the London Plan) at the time of the submission of the relevant reserved matters application for Phases 2A, 2B, 3B, 4A and 4B; G) Code for Sustainable Homes Pre-Assessment; H) BREEAM Pre-Assessment (where non-residential development proposed); I) Daylight and Sunlight Report, including shadow plot diagrams; J) Details of playspace, amenity space and landscaping strategy including boundary treatments taking into consideration the probable requirement for acoustic fencing along the northern boundary of the site and the recommendations set out within the approved Wind Environment Assessment (the details of public realm and public open space landscaping are required by separate condition); K) A statement detailing how the landscaping proposals contribute to mitigation measures for nesting birds, the enablement of species to migrate such as hedgehogs and other small mammals through gaps in fencing and ecological enhancements detailed within the approved Biodiversity Strategy and Ecological Surveys; L) Details of parking and servicing, both off-street and on-street and including details of Electric Vehicle Charging Points, wheelchair accessible parking spaces, and car club spaces; M) Details of bicycle storage for residential accommodation; bicycle storage for staff of the non-residential uses and bicycle parking for visitors to the non-residential floorspace; N) Details of the works to the public realm and highways, road layout including auto-track templates to demonstrate that adequate manoeuvring area is provided, any traffic calming measures and a proposed adoption plan (the details of which are also required in relation to the S.38 / S.278 Agreement) and external lighting; O) Planning Statement; P) Ecological Survey of priority habitats and priority species and other noted species, including (but not limited to) Bat Surveys carried out in accordance with Bat Conservation Trust Survey Guidelines; Q) External Lighting Strategy prepared with advice from an ecologist and specifically considering the impact of light-spill on priority species;  R) Statement of Community Involvement; S) Affordable Housing Statement (informed by the financial viability appraisal, required under the S106 Agreement); T) Updated Phasing Strategy (if relevant);  The scope and detail of each reserved matters application shall be in proportion to the amount and scale of development proposed.  The proposed external lighting scheme shall comply with the advice given at BS 5389 Part 9, with regards to upward light and light pollution and lighting of public amenity areas and ILE guidance on 'Reduction of Obtrusive Lighting 2005' and also consider the recommendations of the Bat Conservation Trust and Natural England. The external lighting scheme shall be approved in consultation with the Canal & River Trust.  The development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved plans and details.   Any trees or shrubs that die within five years of planting shall be replaced with the same species of the same size or an approved alternative and to the satisfaction of the Local Planning Authority during the next planting season.  Tree species shall specifically exclude the use of Quercus robur and not result in a tree species monoculture.  Reason: In order that the Local Planning Authority could be satisfied with the details of the proposed development. | Each Reserved Matters submission for a Phase / reserved matters area of development that incorporates altered, reconfigured or new public open space or new areas of public realm, as illustrated on the approved drawing PL_Out_007 A, shall include the following information for the Council's written approval:  A) Updated Design and Access Statement and supporting Design Code, which shall provide details of how the design principles and commitments established by the approved Design and Access Statement, Design Code and Wind Environment Assessment are achieved (the information shall be limited to the public open space and / or community open space); B) Soft landscaping: including grass and turf areas, hedges, shrub and herbaceous areas, and tree strategy including species type and size at planting; C) Hard landscaping: including ground surfaces, kerbs, edges, ridge and flexible paving, seating or other public realm furniture, steps, and any synthetic surfaces; D) Enclosures and boundary treatments, including types, dimensions and finishes of walls, fences, screen walls, barriers, bollards, rails, retaining walls and hedges; E) play equipment, including safety surfacing; F) A statement detailing how the landscaping proposals contribute to mitigation measures for nesting birds, the enablement of species to migrate such as hedgehogs and other small mammals through gaps in fencing and ecological enhancements detailed within the approved Biodiversity Strategy and Ecological Surveys, particularly the early planting of native hedgerow and / or thicket planting along the southern boundary of the site at the beginning of Phase 2A in order to establish habitat prior to the commencement of Phases 3A and / or 4A; G) External Lighting Strategy prepared with advice from an ecologist and specifically considering the impact of light-spill on priority species;  H) Work phasing plan.  The landscaping scheme for the area adjacent to the Grand Union Canal (contained within Phases 3A and 4A) shall be approved in consultation with the Canal & River Trust.   The proposed external lighting scheme shall comply with the advice given at BS 5389 Part 9, with regards to upward light and light pollution and lighting of public amenity areas and ILE guidance on 'Reduction of Obtrusive Lighting 2005' and also consider the recommendations of the Bat Conservation Trust and Natural England. The external lighting scheme shall be approved in consultation with the Canal & River Trust.  The development shall thereafter be carried out in accordance with the approved plans and details.   Any trees or shrubs that die within five years of planting shall be replaced with the same species of the same size or an approved alternative and to the satisfaction of the Local Planning Authority during the next planting season.  Tree species shall specifically exclude the use of Quercus robur and not result in a tree species monoculture.  Reason: In order that the Local Planning Authority could be satisfied with the design of the public space and because the provision of the public open space and the associated children's play space is required in order to provide mitigation for the loss of public open space within the site as a result of the proposals to develop on existing areas of designated public open space and in order to ensure that the resulting development is provided with an acceptable scheme of replacement open space, in accordance with the policy requirements set out at paragraph 74 of the NPPF and policies 7.18, 7.19 and 7.21 of the London Plan 2015;  policies 1.1(e), 1.1(i), 1.2(d) and 5.5 of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV2.18 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | A revised Energy / Sustainability Assessment Report that incorporates a communal gas boiler to supply heat and hot water to Phase 3A shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the LPA in concert with the Phase 3A reserved matters application.  The revised Energy / Sustainability Assessment Report shall provide measures to achieve on-site total regulated C02 emissions reduction in accordance with the percentage savings contained under policy 5.2 of the London Plan 2011 (including any subsequent revisions to the London Plan) at the time of the submission of the reserved matters application for Phase 3A. Details of the design measures incorporated in the Phase 3A development to facilitate future connection to a district heating network shall also be detailed within the submitted Energy / Sustainability Assessment Report.   In the event of a Qualifying Heat Network Operator (QHNO) being identified by the Council, the Council may serve notice upon the Developer to connect the Qualifying Heat Network to the Development to enable the QHN to supply the heating and hot water requirements of Phase 3A (cores M-Q).   The right of the QHNO to connect to Phase 3A shall be subject to the following conditions being satisfied:  i) The proposed tariff structures must protect the interests of the Developer and occupiers, in that total costs for delivery of the service shall be no more than would have been the case if the on-site CHP system had been provided. Tariffs include unit consumption charges, standing charges, management fees and plant replacement funds; ii) connection charges to the network are reasonable and economically viable; and iii)  A service level agreement can be entered into to protect the interests of the Developer and occupiers by way of a guarantee of system availability.  The right to connect shall also be subject to any regulatory changes governing the communal supply of energy.  The Developer shall use all reasonable endeavours to agree the tariffs, charges, service level agreement and all other commercial terms necessary to enable the QHN to connect to and supply heat to the Development. In the event that the network is available to the development prior to completion of construction, and the Developer connects to the network, the developer will be released from obligations to install stand-alone heating or cooling plant. In the event that the network is not available to the development prior to completion of construction, the developer will remain obliged to connect to the network at any economically viable opportunity, but it is recognised that this opportunity may not arise until the end of the economic life of the stand-alone heating or cooling plant.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved.  Reason: To secure the measures set out within the approved Sustainability Report and ensure that the Phase 3A apartment building is designed in a manner which allows for the future connection to a district system and contributes to reducing the use of fossil fuel or other primary energy generation capacity, and to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.5 and 5.6 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1(k) and 1.2(f) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV5.2 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | No development shall commence in relation to Phases 3A and / or 4A, as illustrated on the approved drawing PL_Out_007 A, until details of the following matters are submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority (in consultation with the Canal and River Trust):  A) Risk Assessment and Method Statement outlining all works to be carried out adjacent to the Grand Union Canal; B) Details of the towpath improvement works, including the submission of details of hard landscaping; and C) Work phasing plan.  The extent of the canal towpath improvement works shall be between Maypole Dock and the southern end of Willowbrook Road.  Reason: To prevent the commencement of development on the parts of the master plan development that front the canal without agreeing details of the improvements to the canal towpath, and to ensure that the proposed works do not have any adverse impact on the safety of the waterway users and the integrity of the Navigation, in accordance with policies 7.24, 7.25, 7.27 and 7.28 of the London Plan 2015. | Prior to the commencement of development on each Phase / reserved matters area, a site construction logistics plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.  The submission shall include the following:  A) A summary of the results of the Ecological Survey and the measures to be put in place to secure the necessary mitigation measures to protect priority species such as nesting birds, bat roosts and other noted species during the clearance of vegetation, felling of trees and demolition and construction works, including a commitment to employ a suitably qualified ecologist to oversee any works affecting priority habitats, priority species and other noted species; B) The number of on-site construction workers and details of the transport options and parking facilities for them; C) anticipated route, anticipated number, frequency and size of construction vehicles entering/exiting the site per day, and capping the maximum number of lorry movements to 30 trips per day;  D) evidence that the use of the Grand Union Canal has been considered for transporting the demolition waste and reducing the impact of lorries on the local road network; E) that appropriate measures are put in place to facilitate the operation of the E5 bus route and associated bus stops during construction works; F) delivery times and booking system (which is to be staggered to avoid morning and afternoon school-run peak periods); G) route and location of site access for construction traffic and associated signage; H) management of consolidated or re-timed trips; I) Details of noise/vibration and dust mitigation measures and monitoring arrangements for noise, vibration and dust by suitably qualified noise and air quality specialists.  Noise/vibration and dust mitigation measures must accord with the Mayor's 'Best Practice Guidance: The control of dust and emissions from construction and demolition ' (2006) and BS 5228 Parts 1 & 2;  J) details of site security and the erection and maintenance of security hoarding including decorative displays and facilities for public viewing, where appropriate; K) secure, off-street loading and drop-off facilities; L) vehicle manoeuvring and turning, including swept path diagrams to demonstrate how construction vehicles will access the site and be able to turn into and emerge from the site in forward gear and including details of any temporary vehicle access points; M) details as to the location(s) for storage of building materials and construction debris and contractors offices; N) procedures for on-site contractors to deal with complaints from members of the public; O) measures to consult cyclists, disabled people and the local schools with regard  to delivery times and necessary diversions; P) details of all pedestrian and cyclist diversions; Q) a commitment to be part of Considerate Constructors Scheme; and R) confirmation of use of TfL's Freight Operator Recognition Scheme (FORS) or similar  Prior to the commencement of any site work, all sensitive properties surrounding the site shall be notified in writing of the nature and duration of the works to be undertaken, and the name and address of a responsible person to whom enquiries / complaints should be directed. These details shall also be displayed at regular intervals around the site construction compound.  The development shall be carried out strictly in accordance with the details so approved.  Any areas to be used for the storage of building materials or other site activities outside of the relevant phase of the development shall be returned to the original condition immediately following the practical completion of the development.  Reason:  To ensure appropriate mitigation measures to protect the amenity of local residents and ensure adequate highway and site safety; and also to ensure that protected species are appropriately safeguarded,  in accordance with policies 5.3, 5.18, 6.3, 7.14, 7.15 and 7.19 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e), 1.1(f) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; Ealing's SPG 10: Noise and Vibration; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012); Greater London Authority 'The control of dust and emissions during construction and demolition' (July 2014); BS 5228-1:2009 - Code of practice for noise & vibration control on construction & open sites-Part 1: Noise; The Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981 (as amended) and The Conservation of Habitats and Species Regulations 2010. | Prior to the commencement of development on each Phase / reserved matters area, a Site Waste Management Plan shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The Site Waste Management Plan shall demonstrate how the procurement of materials for the development would promote sustainability, including by use of low impact, sustainably sourced, reused and recycled materials, including reuse of demolition waste, use of local suppliers and by reference to the BRE's Green Guide Specification.   The development shall be carried out in accordance with the particulars so approved.  Reason:  To ensure sustainable procurement of materials which minimises the negative environmental impacts of construction in accordance with policies 5.3 and 5.18 of the London Plan 2015, policies 1.1 (k) and 1.2 (f) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV5.2 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Prior to the commencement of development on each Phase / reserved matters area (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works), details in line with the criteria specified in Ealing's adopted Supplementary Planning Guidance 10 (Noise and Vibration) shall be submitted to and approved by the Local Planning Authority, including, as appropriate, the noise exposure category and the BS4142 rating noise. The details shall also include the building envelope noise mitigation measures with windows closed and other means of ventilation provided and screening for external amenity areas where necessary.    The details shall also address the sound mitigation measures provided between the ceiling and floor of the non-residential and residential units and the sound mitigation measures provided between the ceiling and floor of the energy centre(s) and residential units (where relevant).  The details as approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of any residential units in the relevant Phase / reserved matters area.  Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers, particularly in the locations adjoining the industrial estate to the north and the Phase 4B site at the corner of Havelock Road and Merrick Road, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; and Ealing's SPG10: Noise and Vibration. | Prior to the commencement of development (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works) on each Phase / reserved matters area of development where plant and / or machinery is proposed, details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority to demonstrate that the rating noise level emitted from the proposed plant and machinery at the proposed development, as assessed under BS4142: 1997, shall be lower than the existing background noise level by at least 5 dBA as measured at 3.5 m from the nearest ground floor sensitive facade and 1m from upper floor noise sensitive facades, during the relevant periods of operation.  The details as approved shall be implemented prior to the first occupation of any residential units in the relevant Phase / reserved matters area.  Reason: To ensure a satisfactory standard of residential amenity is provided for future occupiers, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.15 of the London Plan 2015; policy 1.1(j) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; and Ealing's SPG10: Noise and Vibration. | Prior to the commencement of development on Phases 2 to 4 (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works), an air quality assessment report for the existing site and proposed development and written in accordance with the relevant current guidance shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The report should have regard to the air quality predication and monitoring results from the Stage Four of the Authority's Review and Assessment, the London Air Quality Network and London Atmospheric Emissions Inventory. The report shall also include a scheme for air quality mitigation measures to be incorporated into the development based on the findings of the air quality assessment.   The approved air quality mitigation measures shall be incorporated into the development prior to first occupation or use of the development.  Reason: The Air Quality Stage 4 Review and Assessment for the London Borough of Ealing has highlighted that this area currently experiences or is likely to experience exceedances of Government set air quality standards and air quality mitigation is required. It is necessary that future occupiers are not exposed to poor air quality that could have a negative impact on health and as such, mitigation would be necessary in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012 and policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Prior to the commencement of development on each Phase / reserved matters area (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works), details shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority for the installation in each dwelling of an Ultra-Low NOx boiler with maximum NOx Emissions of under 40 mg/kWh.   The approved boilers shall be incorporated into the development prior to first occupation or use of the development.  Reason: To minimise the impact of building emissions on local air quality, in the interests of health, in accordance with policies 3.2 and 7.14 of the London Plan 2015; policies 1.1(e) and 1.1(j) of Ealing's Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | Prior to the commencement of development on Phases 2 to 4 (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works), a soil contamination investigation and risk assessment for that relevant phase of the development shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. This contamination investigation and risk assessment should include:   A) a survey of the extent, scale and nature of contamination;  B) an assessment of the potential risks to:- human health, property (existing or proposed) including buildings, crops, pets, woodland and service lines and pipes, adjoining land, groundwaters and surface waters, ecological systems;  C) A detailed soil contamination remediation scheme;   The soil contamination investigation must be conducted in accordance with DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'.   The soil contamination remediation scheme must include all works to be undertaken, proposed contamination remediation objectives and contamination remediation criteria, timetable of works and site management procedures. The scheme must ensure that the site will not qualify as contaminated land under Part 2A of the Environmental Protection Act 1990 in relation to the intended use of the land after remediation.  Reason: To protect the health and living conditions of residents of the new development in accordance policy 1.1(e) of the Ealing Development (or Core) Strategy (2012); policy 5.21 of the London Plan 2015; policies LV5.21 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012), and DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'. | The approved soil contamination remediation scheme must be carried out in accordance with the approved details. The Local Planning Authority must be given two weeks written notification of commencement of the remediation scheme works.   Following completion of measures identified in the approved remediation scheme, a verification report that demonstrates the effectiveness of the remediation carried out must be submitted to the Local Planning Authority for information.   The verification report submitted shall be in accordance with the Environment Agency guidance 'Verification of Remediation of Land Contamination', Report: SC030114/R1'.  Reason: To protect the health and living conditions of residents in the area in accordance policy 1.1(e) of the Ealing Development (or Core) Strategy (2012), policy 5.21 of the London Plan 2015; policy LV5.21 and 7A of Ealing's Development Management DPD; the National Planning Policy Framework (2012), and DEFRA and the Environment Agency's 'Model Procedures for the Management of Land Contamination, CLR 11'. | Prior to the commencement of development on Phases 2 to 4 (excluding demolition, site clearance and preparation works), a detailed surface water drainage scheme shall be submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority. The scheme shall be consistent with the broad recommendations contained within the approved Flood Risk Assessment (prepared by Peter Brett Association, Project Ref: 27760 Issue 1, dated May 2013) and shall follow the hierarchy for Sustainable Urban Drainage Systems in policy 5.13 of the London Plan.  The approved scheme shall be implemented and subsequently maintained in accordance with the approved phasing arrangements.  Reason: To ensure that the site is adequately drained to reduce the risk of flooding, to improve and protect water quality, improve habitat and amenity and in the interests of the drainage network in accordance with policies 5.12, 5.13 and 5.14 of the London Plan 2015, policy 1.2(m) of Ealing's adopted Development (or Core) Strategy 2012; and policy LV5.12 of Ealing's Development Management DPD. | No development shall commence on Phases 2 to 4 (including demolition, site clearance and preparation works) until an Arboricultural Method Statement (AMS) prepared in accordance with BS 5837:2012 'Trees in Relation to Design, Demolition and Construction' has been submitted to and approved in writing by the Local Planning Authority.   All protection measures must fully detail each phase of the development process taking into account demolition/site clearance works, all construction works and hard and soft landscaping works.  Details shall include the following:  A. Full survey of all trees on site and those within influencing distance on adjacent sites in accordance with BS5837*, with tree works proposals.  All trees must be plotted on a site plan**, clearly and accurately depicting trunk locations, root protection areas and canopy spreads. B. A plan** detailing all trees, shrubs, hedges planned for retention and removal. C. Soil assessments/survey D. Timing and phasing of works E. Site specific demolition and hard surface removal specifications F. Site specific construction specifications G. Access arrangements and car parking H. Level changes I. A Tree protection plan** in accordance with BS5837* detailing
